reviewText: Don't get me wrong, I LOVE C.S.I., the production value is setting a new standard for television of the future. The fifth season is highlighted with some truly phenominal episodes, including the phenominal 2 part finale "Grave Danger".Yet, I'm a little put off by the mentality of the CBS network. They tend to cater to the short-attention span audience... as is, you can miss 3 or 4 episodes, come back a few weeks later and sit down and pick right up with C.S.I., or pretty much anything else on the network. They keep ongoing stories to a bare minimum. You don't really get to know the characters as well as you might on other shows like Veronica Mars, Lost or even X-files for that matter.In reality, C.S.I., is just a MURDER SHE WROTE for the 21st century. It's the same show... with hipper graphics, special effects, a younger, hipper cast and improved technology. Every week, there's a murder, an investigation begins... suspects are presented and the murder is... SOLVED!! EVERY WEEK!!  Wow. I only wish that were true in real life.I always used to joke... Angela Landsbury comes to your town... don't commit a murder, man... she's gonna solve it! Same goes with C.S.I. Yeah, it's Vegas, but man, if the forensic team were really this darn good... crime would be non-existent in that town... and in Miami, and in New York.Not to mention... have you ever heard of so many murderers and drug dealers and arsonists... just folding in and telling the interrogators EVERYTHING. OH, YOU GOT ME!! Here's a detailed description of how I did it... as if you don't already know already you super sleuth.Don't get me wrong... I love C.S.I. William Peterson is one of my favorite actors. Always has been. Ever since he blew me away in TO LIVE AND DIE IN L.A.  The show is unreal good. Great stories (Some times a little far fetched). Great writing. Great acting.  But just look at CBS. All of their shows are the SAME. They are all formulaic. Mystery/suspects/solved... each week.CSI, COLD CASE, NUMBERS, WITHOUT A TRACE, CSI MIAMI, CSI NEW YORK, CRIMINAL MINDS, NCIS... even GHOST WHISPERER. They are all the same. In one hand, very real, with intelligence and elaborate dilemmas, but in the other hand, very unrealistic when the crimes are solved so swiftly and formulaicly.CSI just needs to take a lesson from another great show like VERONICA MARS. A show that took a mystery and treated it real, with complications and misdirection and COVER UP that doesn't solve itself in a week. Then, it will truly be appointment Television for me.
summary: Let's be real... GREAT SHOW... but, FORMULAIC

reviewText: First off, after being away for the last 3 seasons, very little went into celebrate the return of Conrad Ecklie. Season 5 was his comeback season & Marc Vann was never called in for commentary on FORMALITIES, MEA CULPA & ICED which were Vann's key Season 5 episodes.The Blue Paint Killer introduced in Season 3's THE EXECUTION OF CATHERINE WILLOWS came back as well to wreak more havoc on college girls in WHAT'S EATING GILBERT GRISSOM? The key actors from the prequel were all back, Victor Bevine, Taylor Nichols & David Lee Smith who is better known for haing played IA Sargent Rick Stetler on C.S.I. MIAMI. BPK finally got named-Kevin Greer. Greer used his artwork to string Grissom along & used that art to deliver THE most creative suicide note ever.C.S.I. also did the unthinkable. 0n DVD their 100th episode got no acknowledgement whatsoever. It also shows the seeming contempt for writer Jerry Stahl. Stahl scribed an episode that after nearly 9 years is still C.S.I.'s highest rated episode. Not a single Special Feature pays tribute, no commentary on CH-CH-CHANGES, also they never included the 100th Episode Party Celebration in Las Vegas where the Big 4 were in attendance-Jerry Bruckheimer, Ann Donahue, Carol Mendolsohn & Anthony Zuiker. The cast, crew, Stahl, director Richard Lewis & all the guest stars. The 100th episode, this is the milestone for which every show strives & the DVD did less then dick to hi-lite it.Sara's past, hinted as tragic in Season 1's SEX, LIES & LARVAE was brought to the forefront in NESTING DOLLS. We learned Sara's mother killed her father, Grissom brought up the substance abuse that both the Season 4 & 5 DVDs paid little notice to, also the main plot of the episode was ignored. The murder of Svetlana Morton by her husband-serial wife-abuser Andrew played with menacing skill by Zeljko Ivanek who had worked for Bruckheimer playing Colonel Gary Harrell in BLACK HAWK DOWN. Morton was pure scum, holding his new wife under his thumb, disconnecting the phones, all food under lock & key. The showdown between Sara & Ecklie. Ivanek was Emmy worthy.Stahl outdid himself & shocked television audiences with his next outing, KING BABY. The world of infantilism was used to tell the story. We were taken into the world of adults who opt to be treated like babies with bottles, diapers, enemas, nursing all of it & the King Baby in this case was casino magnate Bruce Eiger who was feared by fellow casino bosses & was in possession files damaging to the city's top law enforcement among them being Sheriff Rory Atwater. Eiger lived in fear of being outed & had in his sprawling mansion, a secret room that served as Eiger's nursery. Also who can forget the performance of the bubbly Edie McClurg as Madge, the owner of the adult baby store Grissom & Nick go to to learn more about infantilism?By far the greatest crime of the Season 5 DVD is again the continued underserving of Paul Guilfoyle. Ellie Brass returns, she needs her dad's help. As ELLIE actually chose not to include Guilfoyle on the commentary, HOLLYWOOD BRASS became another snub. Brass puts his career on the line to rescue Ellie who has now sunk into prostitution. Brass has no reason to care 1 way or another about Ellie, but he STILL remains her father. We learn the identity of Ellie's real father-disgraced Newark, New Jersey detective Mike 0'Toole. He still cares & fights overwhelming odds to save her. More character development, Brass's past in New Jersey is directly referenced. You had Donna Murphy as Los Angeles captain Annie Kramer who like Brass, left Newark after the corruption case was wrapped. Also keeping in mind that they needed a new Ellie. Nicki Lyn Aycox who was so memorable in ELLIE got Bruckheimer to hire her to play Cristina Rush on COLD CASE & was doing so many episodes that C.S.I. needed a new Ellie. With Ellie being a more hardened character, the producers sought a woman to play Ellie in that fashion. Enter Teal Redmann who played Sarah Mitchell on C.S.I. MIAMI in Season 3's MURDER IN A FLASH. Redmann was so amzing in this episode that you didn't care a toss that it wasn't Aycox, in face Redmann proved to be a better Ellie.HOLLYWOOD BRASS had so many things going into it that the fact it got no attention on the DVD is proof alone as to how the DVDs do little to serve the show. The first episode without Grissom-on that alone noteworthy, the first episode missing half the team. You had Brass nearly alone with only Kramer, Warrick & LA detective Matt Glaser played by Matthew Glave to aid him in LA & getting the only other help from back home in the forms of Nick & Doc Robbins. The only thing more disgraceful then Paul Guilfoyle not doing commentary is how he was screwed over by the Emmys when he delivered a command performance. There should have been commentary from Guilfoyle, Glave, Murphy, Redmann as well as from writers Sarah Goldfinger & Mendolsohn & director Bill Eagles. The nonexistent notice of HOLLYWOOD BRASS is the single greatest disgrace of the Season 5 DVD next to no care taken to CH-CH-CHANGES.But THE most annoying thing, the leading charge of the piss-off, what burns my ass is them breaking up GRAVE DANGER into 2 parts. I wanna f()<king know why they absolutely DESTROYED this episode by breaking it up on DVD when it has NEVER, EVER been broken up on television. I refuse to watch GRAVE DANGER on the Season 5 DVD. I had not watched it for years because the breakup ruins it, it disrupts the entire flow of the film. 0n Its premiere on Thursday May 19th & when it was repeated on Wednesday September 21st, 2005, both times it was aired as a single film. Breaking it up on DVD earns the producers rounds of punches to face. It was not until the Blu-Ray/DVD Combo Pack where it was FINALLY put back together as a single film have I been able to watch it again. This infuriates me so much I scratched GRAVE DANGER off the content locator & off the disc 7 Itself. Disc 7's only purpose is for the Special Features. I will not EVER watch GRAVE DANGER like that.

reviewText: Initially I was disturbed when the writers decided to promote Macklie (Mark Vann, superb in his obnoxious portrayal) and split up Grissom's team.  But in spite of this change, the show is still the best crime series on the air, and on DVD!Stories are a lot more complex, and unique:  a man who lives secretly as a baby; a brother who offs his brother for revealing his "secret"; a killer mold and dry ice...and so on.  But what a finale!  Directed by Quentin Tarantino, "Grave Danger" shows why this series is so good:  tight writing, almost unbearable suspense, and a cast that gets better with each episode.  Paul Guilfoyle, George Eads and Jorja Fox, particularly, but they are ALL super.  Please get the sixth season out on DVD soon.  I'm going to miss this show!!!
summary: CSI CHANGES DON'T HURT A BIT

reviewText: The fifth season of C.S.I. saw the innovative series continue to be a ratings juggernaut, despite the fact that some believed the show's quality would dwindle with two spin-off's on the air as well, the original C.S.I. saw the show still going strong. In quite a few of these episodes, Gil Grissom (William Petersen) takes a bit of a back seat as more focus is put on the newly promoted Nick (George Eads), as well as former lab rat Greg (Eric Szamada) who is now in the field with the rest of the crew. We are given more glimpses into the personal lives of the characters than we have in previous seasons, even though it doesn't always work for the better. However, the second half of the season is simply superb, including an investigation in a mental facility which may prove fatal for Sara (Jorja Fox), an investigation into a college stud's mysterious demise, and of course, who can forget the epic season finale? Self confessed fan of the show Quentin Tarantino writes and directs the two part season finale, in which Nick is kidnapped and buried alive, and Grissom and co. race against time to save him. The finale is worth owning this season box set for alone, and it is undoubtadly one of, if not the, best episodes in the show's entire history. All in all, the fifth season of C.S.I. saw that the show still has plenty of fuel left to keep going strong, and it reaffirms that this is still the best prime time crime saga on network TV today.

reviewText: This show has some of the best writing, directing and acting ever produced on TV, and its two-part finale, "Grave Danger," reached levels of greatness unprecedented on TV. Quentin Tarantino unflinchingly explores the darkest taboo themes in human nature, exploiting the worst fears. In this case, being buried alive. It was a masterstroke having Nick Stokes, the carefree resident he-guy playboy of the show, to be the victim. And for once, making a male the victim. In most of their cases, the CSI team commences with cool calm in assembling their evidence and in solving their murder cases; the repetitiveness of their jobs give them a certain immunity to the constant brutality of their work. But here we have Nick Stokes, drugged and placed into a plastic box underground. He has lost all control, and has no way out. Certain to face a slow, agonizing death. We see Nick flailing helplessly and screaming in sheer terror and panic. Watching this is like a real-life nightmare; if this does not leave you shivering, you're made of strong stuff. The implied claustrophobia is staggeringly suffocating: you are placed in the ground with Nick, and you feel his anticipation of the worst of what he knows is certain. Tarantino is a master at manipulative fear-tapping, and nowhere else will you experience such a terrifying identification as here. The director has the entire cast effectively on edge, some of them numbed into shocked silence, others totally freaked out. Highest honors, though, goes to George Eads for his completely unexpected virtuoso performance. He should have won an Emmy. Who would have expected Eads to go from an efficiently competent actor to one of dazzling range of depth? When was the last time any male character was made to seem so vulnerable, so helpless, so completely downright scared crapless?  Eads screams and cries like a boy; his character's adult male control has been taken away from him, and the actor assails the viewer with an unspeakable sense of cold, clammy dread. A woman would react to this as a girlfriend and mother would, but speaking as a male, I cannot imagine a more sinister scenario (short of being castrated) than this. Most movie/tv situations has the male hero nearly always in control, or at least, having a means, a plan, a way out. Not here. It violates the standard dictum of the hero ingeniously conquering all, and therefore, it is a stunning innovation.The one small cavil I have is that the end of the episode did not provide us to see a great emotional catharsis of Nick and the other characters in the final resolution. But that is a minor point. All told, this slow, clautrophobic agony of terror is one of TV's greatest moments.
summary: Finale unprecedented in TV; gripping, horrifying

reviewText: This is definitely one of the top 3 or 4 seasons of CSI ever. As many commentators and reviewers have pointed out, this season ups the disturbing quotient by a lot. Whereas previous seasons would have a few shocking and disturbing episodes scattered here and there, season 5 from the beginning to the end has a pervasive sense of dread and darkness that the other seasons do not have. It is very hard to explain but any hardcore fan of the show who has seen every episode knows it is true. The cases in general are more gory and horrifying than ever before. The only other season that comes as close to this one as far as the brutality of the murders would be season 7, which is my 2nd favorite after this one. All in all this set has some of the very best CSI episdoes ever and if you are like me and like the most the ones that are like mini-movies, there are plenty of those moments here. Highly recommended - also if you don't have any other seasons of CSI this is a good one to start with!
